KTM Komuter's {{convert|175|km|mi|abbr=on}} network has 45 stations. It consists of two cross-city routes, namely the [[Sentul-Port Klang Route|Sentul-Port Klang]] and [[Rawang-Seremban Route|Rawang-Seremban]] lines, plus a [[Rawang-Seremban Route#Rawang-Tanjung Malim Shuttle Route|shuttle service from Rawang to Tanjung Malim]], which began in April 2007.

Transfers between the two main lines can be made at [[Kuala Lumpur Sentral|KL Sentral]], [[Kuala Lumpur Railway Station|Kuala Lumpur]] and [[Putra Komuter station|Putra]] stations. Same-platform or [[cross-platform interchange]] is available at Kuala Lumpur. Passengers to and from stations between Rawang and Tanjung Malim must change trains at [[Rawang station]].

KTM Komuter has made shopping complexes and recreational centres more accessible. The [[Mid Valley Komuter station|Mid Valley station]], which opened in 2004 next to the [[Mid Valley Megamall]], has proved particularly popular.{{Citation needed|date=November 2010}} Other shopping centres located near KTM Komuter stations are [[Subang Parade]], Carrefour Subang Jaya (near [[Subang Jaya Komuter station|Subang Jaya station]]) and [[The MINES]] ([[Serdang Komuter station|Serdang station]]).

Passengers for [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport]] (KLIA) may take the KTM Komuter to [[Nilai Komuter station|Nilai Komuter halt]] and change to an airport bus, or they may change at [[KL Sentral]] station on to the dedicated [[KLIA Ekspres]]. Interchange with the [[RapidKL Rail]] (KL city metro) network is available at [[Bandar Tasik Selatan station]] for the [[Ampang Line]] and at KL Sentral for the [[Kelana Jaya Line]]. Passengers may also transfer  to the Ampang Line in the city centre at [[Bank Negara Komuter station|Bank Negara station]] by means of a 200-metre walk to the [[Bandaraya LRT station]].

KTM Komuter tickets are sold at counters and via vending machines, available at all stations and halts.

The service is subject to overcrowding during rush hours. To help alleviate the problem, the operator introduced a new queuing system to help riders line up when the trains are coming. The lines are painted on the floor with three colour codes representing each of the train set. The system was first implemented at KL Sentral station on 17 October 2008.<ref>{{Cite news |title=KTM implements new queuing scheme for passengers |url=http://thestar.com.my/metro/story.asp?file=/2008/10/24/central/2359467&sec=central |newspaper=The Star |location= Kuala Lumpur |date=24 October 2008 |accessdate=2008-10-26 |author=Michael, Stuart}}</ref> The operator is also considering introducing express services between [[Sungai Buloh]] and [[Kajang]] stations and between Kuala Lumpur and [[Shah Alam]] station during rush hours by the end of 2008.<!----THIS NEEDS UPDATING-----><ref>{{cite news |title=Six trains for new services |url=http://www.nst.com.my/Current_News/NST/Sunday/National/2385838/Article/index_html |newspaper =New Straits Times |date=26 October 2008 |location= Kuala Lumpur}}</ref>

===Stations===

During the construction of the Komuter service, much of the existing lines were retained, with minor alterations (i.e. removal or abandonment of lines and replacement of wooden [[railroad tie|sleeper]]s with concrete ones). Relevant [[Railway platform|station platform]]s were required to be added and heightened to allow easier access to Komuter trains travelling on both directions.

Major pre-independence stations including [[Kuala Lumpur Railway Station|Kuala Lumpur station]], [[Klang Komuter station|Klang station]], [[Port Klang Komuter station|Port Klang station]] and [[Seremban station]] were retained and upgraded to support Komuter services. Smaller, wood-based stations and halts along the line that were built at around the same time as the aforementioned stations were either demolished and replaced by modern brick-and-concrete counterparts, or simply abandoned. The only exception to the rule is the old [[Sentul Komuter station|Sentul station]], which has remained in service years since KTM Komuter's launch, albeit with a replacement platform.

The layouts and sizes of the new station buildings, as of the launch of the service in 1995, vary by location but are generally divided into two classes:

*Railway halts, consisting of a small single-storey structure with only ticket counters (a ticket booth, ticket machines and [[Turnstile|faregate]]s). The stations are usually placed along straightforward dual-lane lines.
*Medium-sized and single-storey stations, housing both the ticket counters and station offices, and typically stationed along three or more lines. Such stations are typically intended to support additional responsibilities, such as managing [[railway signal]]s, controlling [[railroad switch|points]] and handling goods services. The stations themselves are similar in design to the original wood-based stations along the line with slight hints of Western colonial designs (arches, wooden-and-glass windows and wooden doors), but are larger and modernised.

The platforms of the 1995 stations are virtually standardised, down to the design of the passenger [[semicircle]]-crossed shelters, the use of similarly-styled foot crossings to link all platforms, and the diamonds-based brickwork of the platforms.

Depending on the amount of patrons through the years, each station has undergone upgrades or expansions that consist of either increasing the number of ticket counters or opening new facilities for use by passengers or railway staff. Taller, wider [[Canopy (building)|canopies]] were erected on the platforms of most stations to replace narrower, original versions in 2006 and 2007. The pace of the upgrades varies by location.

During the 2000s, new stations such as the [[Mid Valley Komuter station|Mid Valley station]] appeared in more modern designs, consisting primarily of high, curved canopies above the entire platforms. Certain new stations along dual-lane lines are also included with facilities typically reserved for medium-sized stations, such as the [[Rasa Komuter station|Rasa station]]. The [[Kuala Lumpur Sentral]] station, however, is housed under the concrete base of the transport hub, and is stark and utilitarian in design.

